Contingency data: reduce risk of infection by 1/3

determine n required to show significance at p <= 0.05, 80% power, and effect size of 1/3 reduction in current risk of 50%

### simulate NH

drugPower <- function(nold, rnew, rold, deals=10000){
n.hiv.nh <- c(nold,nold) # (new, old)
risk.nh <- c(rold, rold) # (new, old)
alpha.nh <- 0.05
RR.b.nh <- rep(NA, deals)
for (i in 1:deals){
  # the null hypothesis is that the risks are equal
  # simulate both around the non-drug risk
  
  new.b.nh <- sample(c("hiv", "normal"), n.hiv.nh[1], replace=T, prob=c(risk.nh[1], 1-risk.nh[1]))
  old.b.nh <- sample(c("hiv", "normal"), n.hiv.nh[2], replace=T, prob=c(risk.nh[2], 1-risk.nh[2]))
  n.hiv.b.nh <- c(sum(new.b.nh == "hiv"),
               sum(old.b.nh == "normal"))
  risk.b.nh <- n.hiv.b.nh/n.hiv.nh # n.hiv is fixed in all iterations
  RR.b.nh[i] <- risk.b.nh[1]/risk.b.nh[2]
}
RR.null <- RR.b.nh
RR.crit <- sort(RR.null)[alpha.nh*deals]
hist(RR.null, col=rgb(1,0,0,0.7), xlim=c(0,2))

## Simulate effect size

n.hiv <- c(nold,nold) # (new, old)
risk <- c(rnew, rold) # (new, old)
alpha <- 0.05
RR.b <- rep(NA, deals)
for (i in 1:deals){
  # simulate around the new effect size
  
  new.b <- sample(c("hiv", "normal"), n.hiv[1], replace=T, prob=c(risk[1], 1-risk[1]))
  old.b <- sample(c("hiv", "normal"), n.hiv[2], replace=T, prob=c(risk[2], 1-risk[2]))
  n.hiv.b <- c(sum(new.b == "hiv"),
               sum(old.b == "normal"))
  risk.b <- n.hiv.b/n.hiv # n.hiv is fixed in all iterations
  RR.b[i] <- risk.b[1]/risk.b[2]
}
RR.effect <- RR.b
hist(RR.effect, col=rgb(0,0,1,0.7), add=T)

beta <- sum(RR.effect >= RR.crit)/deals
power <- sum(RR.effect <= RR.crit)/deals

return(c(nold,beta,power))
}

drugPower(85, 0.33, 0.5)

## [1] 85.0000  0.1975  0.8025
seqby5 <- seq(20, 100, by=5)

drugN <- matrix(nrow=length(seqby5), ncol=3)
for (i in 1:length(seqby5)){
  drugN[i,] <- drugPower(seqby5[i], 0.33, 0.5)
}

# with alpha = beta, 0.2

n2 <- seq(20, 100, by=5)
boot.pow.of.n <- rep(NA, 100)
snail.pow <- matrix(nrow=length(n2), ncol=1)
R <- 100 # 1000 takes too long... 
alpha <- 0.05 
for (i in 1:length(n2)){
  for (j in 1:R){
    null.dist <- rstable(n=n2[i], alpha=2, beta=-.3, gamma=2, delta=0)
    # Build effect HERE we want and effect size in the means of 2
    effect.dist <- rstable(n=n2[i], alpha=2, beta=-.3, gamma=2, delta=1.6)
    # compute actual effect size
    adif <- median(effect.dist) - median(null.dist)
    # use our old bootstrap
    effect.boot <- tbM(null.dist, effect.dist, R, median, samples=n2[i])
    if (mean(adif<effect.boot)<=alpha){
      boot.pow.of.n[j] <- 1 # indicates that the effect size was shown to be significant
    } else {
      boot.pow.of.n[j] <- 0 # indicates failure to show significance
    }
  }
  snail.pow[i,] <- mean(boot.pow.of.n) # mean of all those 0's and 1's gives the power
}

snail.pow <- cbind(n2, snail.pow)
snail.pow

n2 <- seq(10, 50, by=5)
boot.pow.of.n <- rep(NA, 100)
snail.pow2 <- matrix(nrow=length(n2), ncol=1)
R <- 100 # 1000 takes too long... 
alpha <- 0.2 # set equal to beta, which is 0.2 because power is 0.8 and is 1-beta
for (i in 1:length(n2)){
  for (j in 1:R){
    null.dist <- rstable(n=n2[i], alpha=2, beta=-.3, gamma=2, delta=0)
    # Build effect HERE we want and effect size in the means of 1.6
    effect.dist <- rstable(n=n2[i], alpha=2, beta=-.3, gamma=2, delta=1.6)
    # compute actual effect size
    adif <- median(effect.dist) - median(null.dist)
    # use our old bootstrap
    effect.boot <- tbM(null.dist, effect.dist, R, median, samples=n2[i])
    if (mean(adif<effect.boot)<=alpha){
      boot.pow.of.n[j] <- 1 # indicates that the effect size was shown to be significant
    } else {
      boot.pow.of.n[j] <- 0 # indicates failure to show significance
    }
  }
  snail.pow2[i,] <- mean(boot.pow.of.n) # mean of all those 0's and 1's gives the power
}

snail.pow2 <- cbind(n2, snail.pow2)

With the simulated distributions of snail sizes, power of 0.8 at alpha=0.05 to show an effect size of 1.6 inches is achieved at n=65. This of course highly depends on the sample distributions used/generated using rstable()…

Using the same simulated distributions and setting alpha=beta=0.2 (1-beta = power = 0.8), the required n for power of 0.8 drops to n=30.
